efore re-applying the patch elsewhere.\n\n## §10 Claude Desktop SSH / Coder Connect to workspaces\n\n**Status ⏳ (as of 2026-05-25): broken end-to-end on Windows — don't recommend it.** Two independent bugs:\n1. Coder Connect's embedded DNS returns empty answers for workspace hostnames even when the GUI shows \"Connect ON\" (filed: coder/coder-desktop-windows#170).\n2. Claude Desktop constructs hostnames as `main.<workspace>.<user>.coder` instead of the `<workspace>.coder` format Coder Connect publishes.\n\nClaude Desktop's SSH client is a bundled Node library — it **ignores `~/.ssh/config` and does not support `ProxyCommand`**, so the `coder ssh --stdio` alias trick always fails with `Timed out while waiting for handshake`. Only direct TCP via Coder Connect can ever work.\n\n**Recommend instead:** run Claude Code *inside* the workspace (browser editor, or `coder ssh <workspace>` from a real terminal). It's pre-installed in claude-code-bmad workspaces.\n\n**Diagnostics if investigating anyway:**\n- Claude Desktop logs: `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\logs\\main.log` (search `LocalSessions.testSSHConnection`)\n- Routing truth-test (bypasses ssh config entirely): `ssh -F nul coder@<workspace>.coder`\n- NRPT rule present? `Get-DnsClientNrptRule | ? { $_.Namespace -match 'coder' }`\n- **Gotcha:** restarting the \"Coder Desktop\" Windows service deletes the Wintun adapter + NRPT rule. `Restart-Service` leaves it broken — toggle Connect OFF/ON in the tray app, or reboot.\n\n## §11 Windows agent stuck on a stalled binary download (monolith-* templates)\n\n**Symptom:** In a monolith-* workspace, the Linux agents (`sql-server`, `localstack`) connect normally but the `main` agent (a **Windows** container, `os = \"windows\"` in the template) sits in `timeout`. The pod is `Running`, images cached, `github-pat` present, PVCs bound — none of §1–§3 apply.\n\n**Confirm:**\n```sh\nkubectl logs <main-pod> -n coder-<workspace> --tail=5\n```\nThe log shows a single line — `Fetching coder agent from https://coder.pageupinternal.cloud//bin/coder-windows-amd64.exe` — and *stays* on it across repeated checks (poll a few times ~45s apart; verified stuck 12+ minutes in one incident). The Windows bootstrap makes **one** download attempt with no retry or timeout: if the transfer stalls, it hangs indefinitely.\n\nDon't confuse this with a *slow but progressing* startup: the `timeout [<seconds>]` flag on the agent is advisory (default `connection_timeout` is 120s and monolith templates don't raise it) — an agent that's genuinely still downloading will connect late on its own. Stuck-on-the-same-log-line across several minutes is the discriminator.\n\n**Fix:** `coder restart <workspace> --yes`. The fresh pod re-attempts the download — in the verified incident the agent connected **47 seconds** after restart (vs. never on the first attempt). A restart is safe here: the stall happens before the agent ever ran, so there's no workspace state to lose.\n\n**Long-term:** raise `connection_timeout` on the Windows `coder_agent` in monolith templates so transient slowness isn't flagged as failure, and/or wrap the bootstrap download in a retry. Until then, \"Windows main agent timed out, Linux siblings fine → check the fetch log line → restart\" is the play.\n\n## Reporting style\n\nWhen you finish a diagnosis, report: (a) confirmed root cause with the evidence line, (b) the fix applied or proposed, (c) what remains unhealthy if anything — in a short status table per agent/pod when multiple components are involved. Never declare a workspace healthy without seeing all agents `connected` and `workspace.health.healthy: true`.\n\n\nARGUMENTS: Investigate whether the Coder CDE (coder.pageupinternal.cloud) AKS cluster is running out of subnet / pod IP range. Symptoms: workspace pods intermittently stuck, agents timing out / not connecting, backend service pods (postgres, mock-ai-stack) getting IPs (10.2.0.x) but connection refused. User was told the subnet is running out of IP range and 